characteristics.participants:
42 preterm infants with planned extubation
Inclusion criteria


Gestational age 26–36 + 6 weeks;

With respiratory distress;

Presenting within 15 days of life;

Requiring invasive ventilatory support for at least 12 hours.

Exclusion criteria


Major congenital malformation;

Known/suspected chromosomal anomalies;

Upper airway anomalies;

Severe perinatal asphyxia;

Born outside the study centre.

characteristics.interventions:
Following extubation (based on specific predefined criteria), infants were randomised to:


nHFOV for extubation (n = 43):nHFOV delivered via SLE 6000 ventilator (Surrey, UK) with the following initial settings: 

Frequency 10–12 Hz;

I:E ratio 1:1;

Amplitude 25–35 cm H2O (titrated based on visible chest oscillations and PCO2);

Pmean 8 –10 cm H2O (titrated on oxygenation).

nIPPV for extubation (n = 43):nIPPV delivered via Dragger Babylog 8000 plus ventilator (Lϋbeck, Germany) with the following initial settings: 

PIP 2 cm H2O above the pre‐extubation set PIP on mechanical ventilation;

PEEP 4–6 cm H2O or identical to PEEP during mechanical ventilation;

Ti 0.30–0.45 s;

Pmean 8–10 cm H^2 O;

RR 40–50 breaths/min;

Flow 8–10 L/min.

The study had specified criteria for weaning, discontinuation, up gradation and failure of the intervention/control.
Both modes were delivered via Fisher Paykel FlexiTrunkTM interface using sizes as per manufacturer (Fisher‐Paykel, Auckland, NZ). Cycling of prongs and masks was done every 4 h. Chin straps were not used. The FiO2adjusted to maintain SpO2between 90% and 95%

characteristics.outcomes:
Primary outcomes


Extubation failure within 72 hours

Secondary outcomes


Reintubation rate;

Invasive ventilator‐free days;

SpO2/FiO2ratio;

Composite duration of oxygen supplementation/ventilation support;

PCO2and pH 12 hours post intervention;

IVH (above grade 3);

Composite BPD/mortality;

Rate of feeding intolerance;

Time taken to full enteral feeds;

Pulmonary air leaks.
